a Staff Sergeant from the [[Special Forces (United States Army)|U.S. Special Forces]] Operational Detachment Alpha (ODA) 572 described the caves:<ref name=\"pbs\"/>\n\n{{quote|Again, with the caves, they weren't these crazy mazes or labyrinths of caves that they described. Most of them were natural caves. Some were supported with some pieces of wood maybe about the size of a 10-foot by 24-foot room, at the largest. They weren't real big. I know they made a spectacle out of that, and how are we going to be able to get into them? We worried about that too, because we see all these reports. Then it turns out, when you actually go up there, there's really just small [[bunker]]s, and a lot of different ammo storage is up there. \u2013 Jeff, Staff Sgt. ODA 572<ref name=\"pbs\">{{citation |title=Against Terror: Interview: U.S. Special Forces ODA 572 |publisher=PBS|work=[[Frontline (American TV program)|Frontline]] |date=July 9, 2002}}</ref>}}\n\nThe complex later was retaken by the Taliban, and served as an important base for the [[Taliban insurgency]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/isis-unable-stay-osama-bin-ladens-tora-bora-fortress-long-1626369|title=Isis unable to stay in Osama Bin Laden's Tora Bora fortress for long|work=[[International Business Times]]|author=Ludovica Iaccino|date=15 June 1017|accessdate=20 June 2017}}</ref> In 2017, Tora Bora was [[Battle of Tora Bora (2017)|attacked and captured]] by the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant \u2013 Khorasan Province]] (ISIL-K),<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/14/world/asia/isis-captures-tora-bora-afghanistan.html|title=ISIS Captures Tora Bora, Once Bin Laden's Afghan Fortress|last1=Nordland|first1=Rod|last2=Abed|first2=Fahim|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=14 June 2017|accessdate=16 June 2017}}</ref> though the [[Afghan National Army]] soon recaptured it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2017/06/17/world/asia/ap-as-afghanistan.html|title=Afghan Official: Afghan Security Forces Recaptured Tora Bora|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Associated Press|date=17 June 1017|accessdate=20 June 2017|author-link=Associated Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2017/06/17/afghan-official-afghan-security-forces-recaptured-tora-bora.html|title=Afghan Official: Afghan security forces recaptured Tora Bora|work=Fox News|date=17 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Afghanistan|Paleontology|Asia|History}}\n\n* [[Qanat#Afghanistan|Qanat]]\n* [[Zhawar]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/al-qaeda/11469138/Inside-Osama-bin-Ladens-al-Qaeda-Tora-Bora-lair-in-Afghanistan-in-pictures.html Photo Gallery]  \u2013 ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]''\n* [https://nypost.com/2015/03/13/photos-reveal-bin-ladens-life-at-tora-bora-compound/ Article on photographs] \u2013 ''[[The New York Post]]''\n\n{{War on Terror|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Caves of Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Caves used for hiding]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Nangarhar Province]]\n", "name_user": "\u0645\u0627\u0646\u064a", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tora_Bora"}
